<font color="#FF0000">AGENT ORANGE</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 31 15:07:04 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
WASHINGTON -- Vietnam veteran Rockne Harmon's voice cracks when he talks <br>
about feeding his 2-year-old son, who barely walks and talks. <br><br>
  The child lost one eye to a rare cancer when he was an infant and faces a <br>
recurrence of the disease, explains the teary-eyed Oakland, Calif. <br>
prosecutor and U. S. Naval Academy graduate. <br><br>
  His brother, Jim, a West Point graduate who also served in Vietnam, said <br>
he watched his 12-year-old daughter die of a rare lung tumor last year.  <br><br>
  The Harmons, while serving in different branches of the service, shared a <br>
common plight -- Exposure to the herbicide Agent Orange. <br><br>
  &quot;They sprayed it on us and told us to hold our breath,&quot; said Jim Harmon, <br>
a lawyer from Garden City, N.Y.  &quot;Twenty-five years later we're still <br>
trying to figure out why we were told to hold our breath.&quot; <br><br>
  That exposure to Agent Orange is killing their children, they said. <br><br>
  Convincing the government of that link is another matter, however. <br><br>
  The Harmons spoke Sept. 9 before the latest group of scientists and <br>
doctors told by Congress to try to determine whether existing research <br>
supports the connection between a chemical in the defoliant, dioxin, and a <br>
host of rare cancers and ailments in veterans and their families.  Agent <br>
Orange was sprayed to destroy jungle and ground cover the North Vietnamese <br>
were using to launch sneak attacks against U. S. forces. <br><br>
  For the Harmons, other veterans and their widows who came to Washington <br>
from across the country to testify, it was yet another battle in a war that <br>
for them did not end when Saigon fell in 1975. <br><br>
  One-by-one, they beseeched the panel to convince the government that <br>
Agent Orange is responsible for their health problems. <br><br>
  &quot;Now, instead of fighting for this country, I'm fighting the government <br>
of this country,&quot; said HAROLD JACKSON, a Vietnam Army veteran from Houston, <br>
who is suffering from degenerative immune and nervous system disorders that <br>
have left him wheel-chair bound.  &quot;Don't allow the government to wait for <br>
us to die off.&quot; <br><br>
  The Department of Veterans Affairs last year began providing benefits to <br>
Vietnam veterans suffering several diseases believed to be related to Agent <br>
Orange exposure.  They are an ailment that causes numbness and tingling <br>
known as peripheral neuropathy, non-Hodgkins lymphoma, soft-tissue sarcoma <br>
or a skin condition known as chloracne. <br><br>
  But there are many illnesses -- including lung cancer -- which the <br>
government does not accept as Agent Orange-related. <br><br>
  The most recent National Academy of Sciences committee, tasked by <br>
Congress two years ago to make recommendations to the Secretary of Veterans <br>
Affairs on the link between Agent Orange and ailments in Vietnam veterans, <br>
expects to complete its report by July 1993, said the panel's chairman, Dr. <br>
Harold Fallon. <br><br>
  Some of the experts who testified, later privately-questioned whether <br>
this latest panel was suited to make recommendations on Agent Orange.  Its <br>
members were chosen because they have not been involved in the Agent Orange <br>
controversy before.  But while that may mean they bring a fresh look to the <br>
issue, critics say, it also means they do not have the background to <br>
understand the politics that may have shaped conclusions in the past. <br><br>
  Over 12 million gallons of Agent Orange were sprayed on forests and <br>
jungles during the war in Vietnam, said Steven Stellman, an epidemiologist <br>
who served as an Agent Orange exposure consultant to the U. S. District <br>
Court in White Plains, N.Y., where several of the defoliant manufacturers <br>
settled a class-action lawsuit filed by 60,000 Agent Orange veterans. <br><br>
  &quot;One would think that a problem of such potential public health <br>
importance would by now have been satisfactorily addressed by the <br>
scientific community,&quot; Stellman told the panel.  &quot;The astonishing fact is <br>
that even today only a handful of hotly disputed studies have been <br>
published.  There has not been a single cancer study with a credible <br>
exposure assessment and the CDC [Centers for Disease Control]...has given <br>
the whole assignment up as impossible.&quot; <br><br>
  An earlier National Academy of Sciences study chided CDC officials for <br>
their 1987 decision to give up the Agent Orange studies because they said <br>
it was impossible to find where troops were stationed and where Agent <br>
Orange was sprayed. <br><br>
  Instead, the CDC made a bio-chemical analysis of blood drawn almost 20 <br>
years after troops were exposed.  They found little evidence of exposure. <br><br>
  Retired Navy Adm. Elmo R. Zumwalt, who during the war ordered the <br>
spraying of Agent Orange and whose son, a Vietnam veteran, later died of <br>
cancer, provided documents to the panel that he said showed how former <br>
President Ronald Reagan tried to influence the CDC study. <br><br>
  &quot;I've seen it take half a century to right the wrongs against the <br>
Japanese, a quarter century to admit it was wrong to submit soldiers ... to <br>
radiation in the desert,&quot; Zumwalt said.  &quot;I hope we'll live to see the day <br>
when the manipulation of Agent Orange data is corrected.&quot; <br><br>
  Doctors treating Agent Orange victims say the costs associated with doing <br>
definitive tests proving dioxin exposure in now sick veterans are very high <br>
and health insurance plans do not cover them. <br><br>
  &quot;A half-dozen tests cost about $800 apiece,&quot; said Dr. Michael Harbut, a <br>
Michigan occupational and environmental medicine expert. &quot;It's just not <br>
feasible&quot; to test everyone. <br><br>
  Harbut said he is treating three Vietnam veterans -- one former Marine, <br>
one airman and one soldier -- who suffered a variety of ailments apparently <br>
caused by Agent Orange that appeared anywhere from months to up to 12 years <br>
after they came home from the war. <br><br>
  &quot;Some get sick sooner, some later and some not at all,&quot; he said. <br><br>
  That was the experience Paulette Boland, the widow of an Army ammunition <br>
keeper who served in Vietnam. <br><br>
  Boland lost her 9-year-old son Brett to a rare brain tumor 10 years ago. <br><br>
  Six months ago, her 45-year-old husband, Robert, died of another rare <br>
brain tumor in the same region of the brain. <br>

